<DOC>
<DOCNO> FR940228-1-00165 </DOCNO>
<PARENT> FR940228-1-00010 </PARENT>
<TEXT>
 
<!-- PJG STAG 4702 -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=21 g=1 f=3 -->
&bull;Acceptable third-party guarantees should include performance bonds, letters of credit, third-party escrow
arrangements, and certificates of deposit. [San Francisco] 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
2. Under what conditions will each type of instrument be used? 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
&bull;These measures should be used for institutions that close or institutions that don't properly repay any required
refunds. [New York] 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
&bull;These measures should be used only if the institution can find no other way to prove its financial status. The
institution should have an opportunity to negotiate with the Department before the third-party guarantees are imposed.
[Kansas City] 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
&bull;These measures should be used anytime the Secretary determines that the institution is not meeting its financial
responsibilities. [San Francisco] 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
&bull;These measures should be used if an institution fails to satisfy a liability established by the Secretary after
an administrative review process. [Atlanta] 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
3. How does the Secretary determine the amount equal to one-half of the annual potential liabilities of an institution,
which is the minimum guarantee amount? 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
&bull;This should be determined based on the institution's retention or refund history. [New York] 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
&bull;The annual potential liability should be defined as the sum of the difference between charges paid by the student
(regardless of the source of payment) and the pro rata
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=21 g=1 f=1 -->
 amounts earned by the institution according to its applicable refund policy. [Atlanta] 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
&bull;The annual potential liability should be based upon the institution's annual Title IV funds multiplied by
one-half of its withdrawal rate. [San Francisco] 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
4. What standards will be used to determine when guarantees in excess of the minimum amount will be required for an institution
that fails to demonstrate financial responsibility? 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
&bull;Guarantees in excess of the minimum amount should be required if the institution must also have funds to make
teach out arrangements. [New York] 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
&bull;Guarantees in excess of the minimum amount should not be imposed. [Kansas City, Atlanta] 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
&bull;Guarantees in excess of the minimum amount should be required when the institution cannot meet its current
financial obligations. [Atlanta] 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
5. How can an institution that does not demonstrate financial responsibility otherwise show that it is capable of
meeting all of its financial obligations. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
&bull;All factors must be analyzed as a whole. [New York] 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
&bull;The Department should use the process used by accrediting agencies to determine financial responsibility.
[New York] 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
&bull;Institutions should be considered financially responsible if they are on reimbursement. [Kansas City, Atlanta]

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
&bull;Institutions should be considered financially responsible if they are funded through an escrow arrangement.
[San Francisco, Atlanta] 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
E. Section 498(c)(4) provides that the determination that an institution has met certain standards of financial
responsibility will be based on an audited and certified financial statement, done in accordance with standards
of the American Institute of Certified Public Accountants. Additional audits may be required. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=21 g=1 f=3 -->
Issues that the community was asked to address and the community's views:
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=21 g=1 f=1 -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
1. When would the Secretary require additional audits, and what additional items should be required for such audits?

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
&bull;The Department should be able to request a more detailed audit of a particular segment of the audited financial
statement. [New York] 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
&bull;The Department should take into account the cost of requests for additional information. [New York] 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
&bull;The Department should be able to request the more frequent submission of audited financial statements in cases
of fraud, abuse, or a negative program review finding. For additional submissions requested at the Secretary's discretion,
it is suggested that the Secretary be willing to look at something other than a full audited financial statement. [Kansas
City] 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
&bull;At the discretion of the Secretary, additional reports could include CPA prepared 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=21 g=1 f=3 -->
pro forma 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=21 g=1 f=1 -->
statements, cash forecasts, enrollment forecasts, and operating budgets with comparisons of actual to budget.
[San Francisco] 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
&bull;There should be no need for interim reports since they are now required annually. If interim information is
requested, it should be unaudited. However, if an institution is seeking relief from a previously imposed fiscal
restriction before its next scheduled statement, the interim statement should be audited. [Atlanta] 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG /STAG -->
