<!-- PJG STAG 4702 -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=21 g=1 f=1 -->
2. What guidelines and time periods should be set for provisional certification? 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
&bull;Each institution should be treated on a case-by-case basis subject to the Secretary's discretion. [New York]

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
&bull;A two-year time period should be used for provisional certification. [New York] 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
&bull;The time period should not exceed three-years and the institution should have the ability to achieve full certification
sooner. [San Francisco] 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
F. Section 498(c)(5) provides that an institution must maintain sufficient cash reserves to ensure repayment of
any required refunds. Institutions that participate in and contribute to a State tuition recovery fund would be exempt
from this requirement. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=21 g=1 f=3 -->
Issues that the community was asked to address and the community's views
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=21 g=1 f=1 -->
: 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
1. What are sufficient cash reserves? How are they measured, what types of funds may be included, and how are they protected
from use for other purposes? 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
&bull;Sufficient cash reserves should be defined as a certain percent of unearned tuition based on the institution's
refund history and established only when there is an indication of a problem or high-risk institution. This could
be part of provisional certification. [New York] 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
&bull;Sufficient cash reserves should be defined as 100 percent of any unearned tuition liability from Title IV awards.
A minority of the group thought an amount to cover loans where the loan guarantee might be invalidated because of fraud
should also be included. Cash reserves should include cash, accounts receivable, and liquid assets that can be converted
to cash within 30 days. [Kansas City] 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
&bull;If the institution has been timely (60 days) in processing refunds for one year, no cash reserves should be required.
If the institution has not been timely, an increasing percentage should be reserved based on the total Title IV funds
processed by the institution. The regulations should be written to provide incentives for institutions with a good
performance record. The Department should take into account whether the refunds were delinquent because of personnel
problems as compared to a poor financial position. When an institution is required to reserve cash, any earnings should
accrue to the institution. Letters of credit should be permitted as a substitute for a cash reserve. [San Francisco]

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
&bull;A cash reserve is sufficient if it equals anticipated refund to be paid during a 30 day period based on the average
of refunds paid during the preceding 12 month period. Cash reserves are defined as cash and cash equivalents plus other
current assets that can be converted to cash within 30 days. Segregation of the cash reserve is not required by law nor
is it desirable. [Atlanta] 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
2. What are the components of a state tuition recovery fund that demonstrates that an institution contributing to
the fund will be able to pay refunds? 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
&bull;If an institution contributes to a State tuition recovery fund they should be exempt automatically from this
requirement. [New York] 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
&bull;The components of a State tuition recovery fund that will demonstrate that an institution contributing to
the fund will be able to pay refunds are those tuition recovery components that will pay a lender the required refund
and/or pay the student the required refund. [Atlanta] 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
3. What information must institutions provide to permit the Secretary to determine that an institution will be able
to use the tuition recovery fund to pay refunds if the institution itself is unable to do so? 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
&bull;An institution should provide a letter from the State that confirms that they will be able to use the State tuition
recovery fund to pay refunds. [New York] 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
&bull;An institution should provide a description of the legal structure of the fund and audited financial statements
so the Secretary may determine that the institution will be able to use the tuition recovery fund. [San Francisco]

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG /STAG -->
</TEXT>
